A Framework for Evaluating Privacy-Utility Trade-off in Vertical Federated Learning

Yan Kang, Jiahuan Luo, Yuanqin He, Xiaojin Zhang, Lixin Fan, Qiang Yang Yan Kang, Jiahuan Luo, Yuanqin He, Lixin Fan and Qiang Yang are with Department of Artificial Intelligence, Webank, Shenzhen, China. Xiaojin Zhang and Qiang Yang are affiliated with Hong Kong University of Science and Technology.Manuscript received April 19, 2005; revised August 26, 2015.
Abstract

Federated learning (FL) has emerged as a practical solution to tackle data silo issues without compromising user privacy. One of its variants, vertical federated learning (VFL), has recently gained increasing attention as the VFL matches the enterprises’ demands of leveraging more valuable features to build better machine learning models while preserving user privacy. Current works in VFL concentrate on developing a specific protection or attack mechanism for a particular VFL algorithm. In this work, we propose an evaluation framework that formulates the privacy-utility evaluation problem. We then use this framework as a guide to comprehensively evaluate a broad range of protection mechanisms against most of the state-of-the-art privacy attacks for three widely-deployed VFL algorithms. These evaluations may help FL practitioners select appropriate protection mechanisms given specific requirements. Our evaluation results demonstrate that: the model inversion and most of the label inference attacks can be thwarted by existing protection mechanisms; the model completion (MC) attack is difficult to be prevented, which calls for more advanced MC-targeted protection mechanisms. Based on our evaluation results, we offer concrete advice on improving the privacy-preserving capability of VFL systems.

Index Terms:
Evaluation Framework, Data Privacy, Vertical Federated Learning.

1 Introduction

DEEP learning (DL) has shown notable success in recent years. A major enabler for the popularity of DL is the availability of a large amount of centralized data. However, in many industries such as finance and healthcare, data are typically dispersed among multiple independent organizations (e.g., institutions and companies) and usually contain sensitive user information. Due to increasingly strict legal and regulatory constraints enforced on user privacy, such as the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), sensitive data from different organizations cannot be directly merged for training deep learning models.

Federated learning (FL) has recently emerged as a feasible solution to tackle data silo issues without sharing private user data. Initially, FL [1] was proposed to build a global model by utilizing data from millions of mobile devices. This setting of FL is categorized as Horizontal FL (HFL), in which participants own disjoint sample instances with the same feature space. Further, FL was extended to the enterprise setting where the amount of participating parties might be much smaller, but privacy concerns are paramount. This setting is categorized as Vertical FL (VFL) [2], in which participants own disjoint features of the same set of sample instances (see Section 2).

Although FL participants do not share their private user data with each other, user data privacy can not be guaranteed. In HFL, recent works [3, 4, 5, 6] demonstrated that the adversary could reconstruct sensitive user information upon observing the exposed model updates. Various protection mechanisms [7, 8, 9, 10, 11] have been proposed to protect HFL against data reconstruction attacks. They essentially reduce the dependency between the exposed model updates and private data, thereby reducing the possible privacy leakage. Several works [12, 13] comprehensively evaluated various protection mechanisms against state-of-the-art private attacks in HFL.

In VFL, current works focus on developing specific protection or attack mechanism for a particular VFL algorithm [14, 15, 16]. To our best knowledge, no work comprehensively evaluates and compares a broad range of protection mechanisms against state-of-the-art privacy attacks for widely-adopted VFL algorithms. The most relevant works [17, 16] focus on only one or two privacy attacks for one specific VFL algorithm. In this work, we aim to fill this gap because privacy issue is crucial in VFL. Such comprehensive evaluations may assist FL practitioners in understanding the pros and cons of existing protection mechanisms, identifying potential privacy vulnerabilities, and guiding them in implementing better privacy-preserving VFL systems. Besides, an evaluation framework that formulates the privacy-utility evaluation problem is also critical as it may help standardize the evaluation process.

The main contributions of this work include:

  • •

    We propose an evaluation framework that formulates the problem of evaluating the trade-off between privacy leakage and utility loss of a VFL system. This framework would serve as a basis for standardizing the FL evaluation process.

  • •

    We apply our proposed evaluation framework to guide the comprehensive evaluations on a broad range of protection mechanisms against most of the state-of-the-art privacy attacks in VFL. These evaluations can help FL practitioners select appropriate protection mechanisms and their corresponding protection parameters according to specific requirements.

  • •

    We build a codebase of the evaluation framework. This codebase has integrated various existing privacy attacks and protection mechanisms and provides extensible hooks for newly proposed privacy attacks and protection methods.

2 Vertical Federated Learning

3 Evaluation Framework

This evaluation framework formulates the evaluation problem by modeling the relationship between the privacy protection and the privacy threat to our proposed VFL architecture. Inspired by the no free lunch theorem [18], we model this relationship via the lens of the protector and the adversary based on privacy leakage ϵpsubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝\epsilon_{p} and utility loss ϵusubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑢\epsilon_{u}:

Definition 1 (Privacy Leakage).

The privacy leakage ϵpsubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝\epsilon_{p} measures the discrepancy between the adversary’s posterior and prior knowledge of the private data, and is defined as:

ϵp=Hp​(Mp​r​i​(𝒜,𝒟,⟨𝒲⟩,𝒫,𝒦),Mp​o​s​(𝒟))subscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝subscript𝐻𝑝subscript𝑀𝑝𝑟𝑖𝒜𝒟delimited-⟨⟩𝒲𝒫𝒦subscript𝑀𝑝𝑜𝑠𝒟\displaystyle\epsilon_{p}=H_{p}(M_{pri}(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{D},\langle\mathcal{W}\rangle,\mathcal{P},\mathcal{K}),M_{pos}(\mathcal{D})) (2)

where 𝒜𝒜\mathcal{A}, 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D}, 𝒲𝒲\mathcal{W}, 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} and 𝒦𝒦\mathcal{K} are five key components of evaluating the privacy leakage. They denote VFL algorithm, private data, privacy vulnerability, protection mechanism and privacy attack, respectively; Mp​r​i​(𝒜,𝒟,⟨𝒲⟩,𝒫,𝒦)subscript𝑀𝑝𝑟𝑖𝒜𝒟delimited-⟨⟩𝒲𝒫𝒦M_{pri}(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{D},\langle\mathcal{W}\rangle,\mathcal{P},\mathcal{K}) measures the adversary’s posterior knowledge about the private data when the adversary applies privacy attack 𝒦𝒦\mathcal{K} to the privacy vulnerability ⟨𝒲⟩delimited-⟨⟩𝒲\langle\mathcal{W}\rangle protected by 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P}. Mp​o​s​(𝒟)subscript𝑀𝑝𝑜𝑠𝒟M_{pos}(\mathcal{D}) measures the adversary’s prior knowledge about the private data 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D}. Hpsubscript𝐻𝑝H_{p} evaluates the discrepancy between the adversary’s prior and posterior knowledge on the data owner’s private data.

Following, we explain the five key components, i.e., 𝒜𝒜\mathcal{A}, 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D}, 𝒲𝒲\mathcal{W}, 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} and 𝒦𝒦\mathcal{K}, in detail:

  • •

    𝒜𝒜\mathcal{A} denotes the VLF algorithm under which the privacy leakage is evaluated. It determines the privacy vulnerabilities that the adversary can leverage to infer the private data.

  • •

    𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D} denotes the private data that the adversary aims to infer and the data owner should protect. It typically involves the features and labels of a dataset.

  • •

    𝒲𝒲\mathcal{W} denotes the privacy vulnerability, which can be any information that the privacy attack can leverage to infer the private data 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D}. Thus, 𝒲𝒲\mathcal{W} should be protected by the data owner through certain protection mechanism. 𝒲𝒲\mathcal{W} is determined by 𝒜𝒜\mathcal{A}. e.g., 𝒲𝒲\mathcal{W} involves intermediate gradients sent to the passive parties for VFL neural networks

  • •

    𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} denotes the protection mechanism that data owners adopt to protect 𝒲𝒲\mathcal{W}. Well-known protection mechanisms include differential privacy, gradient compression, homomorphic encryption and secure multi-party computation.

  • •

    𝒦𝒦\mathcal{K} denotes the privacy attacks that exploits protected 𝒲𝒲\mathcal{W} to infer the private data 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D}.

Definition 2 (Utility Loss).

The utility loss ϵusubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑢\epsilon_{u} measures the discrepancy between the utility of the unprotected federated model g𝑔g and the utility of the protected federated model ⟨g⟩delimited-⟨⟩𝑔\langle g\rangle, and is defined as:

ϵu=Hu​(Mu​(g),Mu​(⟨g⟩))subscriptitalic-ϵ𝑢subscript𝐻𝑢subscript𝑀𝑢𝑔subscript𝑀𝑢delimited-⟨⟩𝑔\displaystyle\epsilon_{u}=H_{u}(M_{u}(g),M_{u}(\langle g\rangle)) (3)

where Mu​(⟨g⟩)subscript𝑀𝑢delimited-⟨⟩𝑔M_{u}(\langle g\rangle) and Mu​(g)subscript𝑀𝑢𝑔M_{u}(g) measure the utilities of the federated model g𝑔g with and without protection 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P}, respectively. Husubscript𝐻𝑢H_{u} evaluates the difference between Mu​(g)subscript𝑀𝑢𝑔M_{u}(g) and Mu​(⟨g⟩)subscript𝑀𝑢delimited-⟨⟩𝑔M_{u}(\langle g\rangle).

Figure 2 depicts the relationship between the privacy leakage and utility loss through the private data, the privacy vulnerability and the joint model. In VFL, all private data 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D} (i.e., xBsuperscript𝑥𝐵x^{B}, xAsuperscript𝑥𝐴x^{A} and yAsuperscript𝑦𝐴y^{A}) are kept local. Thus, the adversary launches a privacy attack 𝒦𝒦\mathcal{K} on the privacy vulnerability 𝒲𝒲\mathcal{W} to infer the data owner’s private data. The privacy vulnerability can be any information that is dependent upon the data owner’s private data but is exposed to the adversary. This cross-party dependency is established through the message m​s​g𝑚𝑠𝑔msg transmitted to the adversary from the data owner. In order to protect private data, the protector (i.e., data owner) applies protection mechanisms 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} to m​s​g𝑚𝑠𝑔msg sent to the adversary to mitigate the privacy leaked ϵpsubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝\epsilon_{p} to the adversary while maintaining the utility loss ϵusubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑢\epsilon_{u} below an acceptable level. This battle between the adversary and the protector can be represented as the problem of how effectively the adversary can learn private information from privacy vulnerabilities against how well the protector can reduce the dependency between privacy vulnerabilities and its private data without causing much utility loss.

As defined in Definition 1 and Definition 2, we need to identify the target private data 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D}, the privacy vulnerability 𝒲𝒲\mathcal{W}, the privacy attack 𝒦𝒦\mathcal{K} and the protection mechanism 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} in order to measure ϵpsubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝\epsilon_{p} and ϵusubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑢\epsilon_{u} and evaluate their trade-off. 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D} is determined by treat models, which we introduce in Section 4. 𝒲𝒲\mathcal{W} is determined by VFL algorithms and exploited by privacy attacks, which we discuss in Section 5 and Section 6, respectively. In Section 7, we introduce protection mechanisms we considered in this work.

4 Threat Models

In this section, we discuss threat models and their key dimensions.

Adversary’s objective. According to the nature of dispersed data in our VFL setting, there can be three adversary’s objectives: (i) labels and (ii) features owned by the active party, and (iii) features owned by the passive party. It is worth noting that the label information owned the active party is an important target for adversaries in VFL compared to HFL. Because in real-world VFL applications such as finance and advertisement, the labels may contain sensitive user information or are valuable assets.

Adversary’s capability. We consider adversaries in this work semi-honest such that the adversary faithfully follows the vertical federated training protocol but it may launch privacy attacks to infer the private data of other parties.

Adversary’s knowledge. In VFL, participating parties typically have blackbox knowledge about each other. However, adversaries may guess some of the knowledge about others according to the information they have. In this work, we assume that the information about the model structure, input shape and number of classes supported by the active party’s task is shared among parties, unless specified otherwise.

According to the key aspects of the threat models discusses above, we obtain three possible threat models, which are summarized in Table I. The three threat models are all valid, but only T1subscriptT1\text{T}_{1} and T2subscriptT2\text{T}_{2} have practical values. The main reason that T3subscriptT3\text{T}_{3} is less practical is that the only information that the party B can get from party A is the intermediate gradient dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B} during training, and thus it is extremely hard for party B to infer the features xAsuperscript𝑥𝐴x^{A} of party A. As a result, we only consider T1subscriptT1\text{T}_{1} and T2subscriptT2\text{T}_{2} in this work.

5 VFL Algorithms

We focus on three practical VFL algorithms that comply with our VFL framework: Vertical Logistic Regression (VLR), Vertical Hetero Neural Network (VHNN) and Vertical Split Neural Network (VSNN). VLR is widely used in financial applications, while VHNN and VSNN are popular in recommendation applications. The three VFL algorithms differ in their adopted models, but follow an unified training procedure (with minor variations). Although all parties in VFL keep their private data local, it is empirically demonstrated [19, 15, 14] that the adversary is able to infer the target private data 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D} of other parties via launching privacy attacks on exposed intermediate results that depend upon 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D}. These intermediate results are privacy vulnerabilities, and should be protected. e.g., when party B is the adversary who wants to recover party A’s labels, party A should protect the intermediate gradient dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B}, model gradient ∇θB∇superscript𝜃𝐵\nabla\theta^{B} and model parameter θBsuperscript𝜃𝐵\theta^{B} because all of them are derived from the loss computed based upon ground-truth labels of party A (see Figure 3).

6 Privacy Attacks

We introduce privacy attacks proposed in literature and discuss the ones we evaluate in this work.

6.1 Existing Privacy Attacks

We surveyed existing privacy attacks complying with our VFL framework (Section 2). Table III summaries these privacy attacks with several important aspects, including privacy vulnerability, number of classes, attacking phase and auxiliary requirement. We explain these aspects as follow:

  • •

    VFL algorithm refers the specific VFL algorithm a privacy attack is originally applied to. We will extend and adjust some of these attacks to our VFL algorithms (see section 6.2).

  • •

    Privacy Vulnerability refers to the information that is leveraged by the privacy attack to recover the private data of the data owner. e.g., in threat model T1subscriptT1\text{T}_{1}, the privacy attacks DL, NS and DS leverage privacy vulnerabilities dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B} to recover the labels of party A.

  • •

    # of Classes refers to the number of classes supported by the active party’s main task, which can be either binary classification or multi-class classification;

  • •

    Attacking Phase refers to the phrase during which a privacy attack is conducted. It can be either training phase or inference phase.

  • •

    Auxiliary Requirement refers to the auxiliary information leveraged by a privacy attack to infer the private data. e.g., MC requires few labeled data to train the attack model while MI requires some labeled data to train the shadow model (see section 6.2).

6.2 Privacy Attacks We Evaluate in This Work

In literature, a privacy attack is typically applied to one particular VFL algorithm. For a comprehensive evaluation on the effectiveness of these privacy attacks, we adjust these privacy attacks to our VFL algorithms. Tabel IV summaries the adjustment of privacy attacks in this work. e,g., the original work applies NS attack solely to VSNN [15] while this work applies NS attack to VLR, VHNN and VSNN.

7 Privacy Protection

We introduce protection mechanisms proposed in literature and discuss the ones we evaluate in this work.

7.1 Existing Protection Mechanisms

Table V categorizes some of the protection mechanisms proposed in literature and summarizes the contexts in which these protections are applied. Below, we introduce each category of these protection mechanisms.

  • •

    Cryptography: Protections in this category utilize cryptographic techniques such as homomorphic encryption and secret sharing to prevent the adversary from accessing the true values of privacy vulnerabilities.

  • •

    Noisy gradient: Protections in this category add random noise to the cut-layer gradients dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B} to reduce the dependency between dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B} and private data, thereby mitigating privacy leakage.

  • •

    Gradient Prune: Protections in this category prune dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B} aiming at reducing the amount of private information exposed to the adversary.

  • •

    Residue Mask: This protection [20] is tailored to residue reconstruction attack. More specifically, it randomly masks some of the elements in residue dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B} to zeros aiming to make the adversary hard to reconstruct dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B} from the model gradient ∇θB∇superscript𝜃𝐵\nabla\theta^{B}.

  • •

    Data Encode: Protections in this category encode the private data (either features or labels) directly and use encoded data to train VFL models. These protections make the adversary difficult to infer the original private data. The degree of difficulty depends on the amount of mix-up or confusion the encoder applies to the private data.

  • •

    Privacy-enhancing module: Protections in this category typically leverage auxiliary modules (and data) to make exposed privacy vulnerabilities less dependent on the private data without compromising the overall utility.

Crypto-based protection mechanisms can achieve semantic security [29] with lossless utility. However, they may introduce orders of magnitudes more computational (e.g., HE) and communication overheads (e.g., MPC). Hybrid protection schemes that combine non-crypto and crypto-based protection mechanisms may be of more practical in real-world applications as they can better balance between privacy, utility and efficiency.

Nonetheless, non-crypto protection mechanisms have two limitations: (i) the effectiveness of the same protection mechanism may vary widely against different attacks in different VFL algorithms; (ii) they require FL practitioners to tweak the protection parameter to balance between the privacy leakage and utility loss. To alleviate these limitations, this work comprehensively evaluates a broad range of existing no-crypto protection mechanisms against most of the state-of-the-art privacy attacks for three VFL algorithms. These evaluations could serve as a guidance for the selection of protections and their protection parameters according to specific requirements.

7.2 Protection Mechanisms We Evaluate in This Work

Gradient Compression (GC) compresses cut-layer gradients dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B} by retaining elements in dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B} that are above a threshold t𝑡t, while setting other elements to 0. t𝑡t is the smallest value of the top π∈(0,1)𝜋01\pi\in(0,1) of the total elements in dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B}. The π𝜋\pi is the ratio of retaining elements in dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B}. A smaller π𝜋\pi indicates a higher compression degree. We use π𝜋\pi as the protection strength parameter for GC.

DiscreteSGD (D-SGD) [19] compresses cut-layer gradients dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B} by discretizing elements in dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B}. It first determines an upper bound l​b=μ−2​σ𝑙𝑏𝜇2𝜎lb=\mu-2\sigma and a lower bound u​b=μ+2​σ𝑢𝑏𝜇2𝜎ub=\mu+2\sigma, where μ𝜇\mu and σ𝜎\sigma denote the mean and standard deviation of dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B}. The N𝑁N controls the compression degree of the D-SGD. A smaller N𝑁N indicates a higher compression degree. We use N𝑁N as the protection strength parameter for D-SGD.

PRECODE [27] embeds a variational bottleneck (VB) into the original network to defend against model inversion attack. VB consists of an Encoder E​n​c𝐸𝑛𝑐Enc and a Decoder D​e​c𝐷𝑒𝑐Dec. The E​n​c𝐸𝑛𝑐Enc encodes the output q𝑞q of the previous network module into a latent distribution 𝒩​(μ,σ)𝒩𝜇𝜎\mathcal{N}(\mu,\sigma) with μ𝜇\mu and σ𝜎\sigma denoting the mean and standard deviation, respectively. The D​e​c𝐷𝑒𝑐Dec takes as input the bottleneck features o∼𝒩​(μ,σ)similar-to𝑜𝒩𝜇𝜎o\sim\mathcal{N}(\mu,\sigma) and generates a new representation q^^𝑞\hat{q}, which is feed into the following network module to continue the training process. For the VB to learn a continuous and complete latent space distribution, the original loss function is extended to include the term Kullback-Leibler​(𝒩​(μ,σ),𝒩​(0,1))Kullback-Leibler𝒩𝜇𝜎𝒩01\text{Kullback-Leibler}(\mathcal{N}(\mu,\sigma),\mathcal{N}(0,1)).

MixUp [26] constructs virtual training samples from samples of original dataset:

x^=γ​xi+(1−γ)​xj,y^=γ​yi+(1−γ)​yj,formulae-sequence^𝑥𝛾subscript𝑥𝑖1𝛾subscript𝑥𝑗^𝑦𝛾subscript𝑦𝑖1𝛾subscript𝑦𝑗\begin{split}\hat{x}&=\gamma x_{i}+(1-\gamma)x_{j},\\ \hat{y}&=\gamma y_{i}+(1-\gamma)y_{j},\\ \end{split} (20)

where (xi,yi)subscript𝑥𝑖subscript𝑦𝑖(x_{i},y_{i}) and (xj,yj)subscript𝑥𝑗subscript𝑦𝑗(x_{j},y_{j}) are two samples drawn from the training dataset, and (x^,y^)^𝑥^𝑦(\hat{x},\hat{y}) is the resulting mixed-up sample. The VFL algorithm uses mixed-up samples to train models instead of the original ones. γ∈(0,1)𝛾01\gamma\in(0,1) controls the linear interpolations of feature vectors and associated labels.

8 Experiments

In this section, we evaluate protection mechanisms chosen in Section 7.2) against privacy attacks chosen in Section 6.2), under practical threat models determined in Section 4 for widely-adopted VFL algorithms described in Section 5.

8.1 Evaluation Task Setup

We have all five key components (i.e., 𝒜𝒜\mathcal{A}, 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D}, 𝒲𝒲\mathcal{W}, 𝒦𝒦\mathcal{K} and 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P}) prepared. We arrange the evaluation into 6 evaluation settings that each corresponds to a suite of evaluation tasks conducted based on the same privacy vulnerability in the same VFL algorithm (i.e., either VLR or VNN) (see Table VI).

Each combination of values of the five components constitutes an evaluation task. e.g., a combination {VLR, yAsuperscript𝑦𝐴y^{A}, dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B}, NS, ISO} indicates that we evaluate the privacy leakage and utility loss when the adversary mounts a NS attack on the privacy vulnerability dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B} in VLR to infer the private data yAsuperscript𝑦𝐴y^{A} that is protected by ISO.

The trade-off between the privacy leakage ϵpsubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝\epsilon_{p} and the utility loss ϵusubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑢\epsilon_{u} of a protection mechanism is controlled by the protection strength parameter. Specifically, noise-based protections adjust the noise level added to the gradients to control the trade-off: for DP-L, we choose the noise level λ𝜆\lambda from the range of [0.0001,0.001,0.01,0.1]0.00010.0010.010.1[0.0001,0.001,0.01,0.1]; for ISO, we experiment with 4 different noise amplifiers: α∈[25,10,5,2.75]𝛼251052.75\alpha\in[25,10,5,2.75]; for Marvell, we experiment with 4 different noise upper-bounds τ∈[12,8,4,2]𝜏12842\tau\in[12,8,4,2]. Prune-based protections manipulate the degree of compression imposed on gradients to control the trade-off: for GC, we choose the retaining ratio π𝜋\pi from the range of [0.1,0.25,0.5,0.75]0.10.250.50.75[0.1,0.25,0.5,0.75]; for D-SGD, we choose the number of bins N𝑁N from the range of [18,12,6,4]181264[18,12,6,4]. For MixUp, we experiment with mixing-up 2, 3, 4 original samples, respectively, to create new training samples. Max-Norm and PRECODE are parameter-free protection mechanisms.

8.2 Datasets and Models

In this work, we focus on binary and 10-class classification tasks. Table IX summarizes our chosen datasets and their corresponding VFL algorithms and models.

FMNIST (i.e., Fashion-MNIST) is used to evaluate protections against feature reconstruction attacks, while the other 8 datasets are used to evaluate protections against label recovery attacks. The Credit, NUSWIDE2-imb and Criteo are for imbalanced binary classification. The Vehicle, NUSWIDE2-bal and BHI are for balanced binary classification. The NUSWIDE10 and CIFAR10 are for 10-class classification (see Appendix B for more detail).

8.3 Performance Quantification

We adopt AUC-ROC and Acc (i.e., accuracy) metrics to evaluate the performance of label recovery attacks and the VFL main classification tasks. For feature reconstruction attacks (i.e., MI), we adopt SSIM (Structural Similarity Index) [30] to measure the attacking performance.

The privacy leakage ϵpsubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝\epsilon_{p} of a protection mechanism (typically with certain protection strength) is measured based on the result of a specific privacy attack, and the utility loss ϵusubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑢\epsilon_{u} is the distance between the utility of unprotected joint model g𝑔g and that of protected one ⟨g⟩delimited-⟨⟩𝑔\langle g\rangle. Table VIII shows our measurements for ϵpsubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝\epsilon_{p} and ϵusubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑢\epsilon_{u}. Note that we estimate the adversary’s prior knowledge on target labels through a random classifier rclssubscript𝑟clsr_{\text{cls}} for label recovery attacks that require no auxiliary data. e.g., for NS attack, AUC​(rcls)AUCsubscript𝑟cls\text{AUC}(r_{\text{cls}})=50.050.050.0, assuming AUC​(ℛNS​(⟨dB⟩))AUCsubscriptℛNSdelimited-⟨⟩superscript𝑑𝐵\text{AUC}\left(\mathcal{R}_{\text{NS}}(\langle d^{B}\rangle)\right)=65.065.065.0, then we have privacy leakage ϵp=65.0−50.0=15.0subscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝65.050.015.0\epsilon_{p}=65.0-50.0=15.0.

8.4 Evaluations for VLR

In this subsection, we conduct evaluation tasks in VLR (see Table VI). We do not apply Marvell to VLR because Marvell requires dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B} with a feature dimension of 2 while many deployed VLR algorithms support 1-dimensional dBsuperscript𝑑𝐵d^{B}. We also do not consider model inversion attack (MI) in VLR since MI has been thoroughly investigated in [17].

8.4.3 Evaluating Protections against Model Completion

In VLR, the adversary party B adds a sigmoid function on top of its trained local model fAsuperscript𝑓𝐴f^{A} to form a complete label prediction network 𝒥MCsubscript𝒥MC\mathcal{J}_{\text{MC}} (no auxiliary training data needed), and then party B uses 𝒥MCsubscript𝒥MC\mathcal{J}_{\text{MC}} to infer labels of party A. Figure 6 depicts PU trade-offs of DP-L, GC, D-SGD, MN and ISO against MC on Credit and Vehicle. Table XII compares optimal PU scores correspondingly.

Figure 6 illustrates that all 5 protections have difficult preventing MC on Credit since their trade-off curves are distant from the bottom-left corner, and only ISO is able to achieve a good PU trade-off on Vehicle when the noise amplifier α𝛼\alpha=2.75. Table XII reports that GC, D-SGD, DP-L and ISO perform mediocrely (SPU∗superscriptsubscript𝑆PUS_{\text{PU}}^{*}=2), and MN performs marginally (SPU∗superscriptsubscript𝑆PUS_{\text{PU}}^{*}=1) on thwarting MC on Credit; ISO and GC are effective in preventing MC on Vehicle (they obtain SPU∗superscriptsubscript𝑆PUS_{\text{PU}}^{*} of 4 and 2, respectively), while D-SGD, MN and DP-L fail to prevent MC on Vehicle (SPU∗superscriptsubscript𝑆PUS_{\text{PU}}^{*}=0). Thus, we have following preference over the 5 protections against MC in VLR:

ISO>GC>DP-L≈D-SGD>MNISOGCDP-LD-SGDMN\displaystyle\text{ISO}>\text{GC}>\text{DP-L}\approx\text{D-SGD}>\text{MN}

Takeaways for VLR:
(1) Generally, ISO and DP-L can thwart NS, DS, DL, RR, GI attacks quite effectively (SPU∗superscriptsubscript𝑆PUS_{\text{PU}}^{*}=4).

(2) The five protection mechanisms evaluated in VLR have difficulty thwarting MC attack.

(3) None of the 5 protections can achieve the best PU-score (SPU∗superscriptsubscript𝑆PUS_{\text{PU}}^{*}=5), manifesting that it is inevitable to lose non-negligible utility to protect privacy using non-crypto protections in VLR. If efficiency is not crucial, crypto-based protections are preferred for VLR.

8.5.2 Evaluating Protections against Model Completion

In VNN, model completion (MC) attack requires auxiliary labeled data to train a complete attacking model (see Section 6.2). We assume the adversary (i.e., party B) has some prior knowledge on labels, and we measure the privacy leakage of a protection mechanism against MC by Ω​(⟨𝒥MC⟩​(xi​n​fB))−Ω​(𝒥loc​(xi​n​fB))Ωdelimited-⟨⟩subscript𝒥MCsubscriptsuperscript𝑥𝐵𝑖𝑛𝑓Ωsubscript𝒥locsubscriptsuperscript𝑥𝐵𝑖𝑛𝑓\Omega(\langle\mathcal{J}_{\text{MC}}\rangle(x^{B}_{inf}))-\Omega(\mathcal{J}_{\text{loc}}(x^{B}_{inf})), where Ω∈{AUC,Acc}ΩAUCAcc\Omega\in\{\text{AUC},\text{Acc}\} and xi​n​fBsubscriptsuperscript𝑥𝐵𝑖𝑛𝑓x^{B}_{inf} is the inference data owned by party B.

We first analyze the privacy leakage trend for each protection mechanism with increasing auxiliary samples in the range of [40, 80, 160, 200, 400]. We find out the adversary generally obtains more knowledge payoff on private labels when it uses a smaller amount (i.e., 40 or 80) of auxiliary samples (see Figure 11 of Appendix C). The intuition behind this phenomenon is that the increment of the attacker’s prior knowledge on private labels becomes larger than that of the attacker’s posterior knowledge on private labels as the number of auxiliary samples increases.

We then investigate the trade-off performance of protection mechanism in the worst-case scenario (WCS), where the MC leads to the most privacy leakage. The WCS happens when the MC is mounted using 80 auxiliary samples on CIFAR10 and 40 samples on the other datasets. Figures 9 and 10 depict PU trade-offs of protection mechanisms against MC in VHNN and VSNN, respectively. Table XV reports optimal PU scores of protections corresponding to Figures 9 and 10.

Figures 9 and 10 show that ISO and DP-L achieve better PU trade-offs than the other 4 protections. Still, all 6 protections have difficulty thwarting MC because their trade-off curves overall have wide distances from the bottom-left corner. Accordingly, Table XV reports that, in VHNN, ISO and DP-L perform mediocrely against MC on all datasets (except BHI) (SPU∗≈2superscriptsubscript𝑆PU2S_{\text{PU}}^{*}\approx 2); GC, D-SGD, MN, and Marvell perform marginally on NUSWIDE2-imb (SPU∗superscriptsubscript𝑆PUS_{\text{PU}}^{*}=1); GC, D-SGD, and MN fail to prevent MC on NUSWIDE10 and CIFAR10 (SPU∗superscriptsubscript𝑆PUS_{\text{PU}}^{*}=0). These results manifest MC is difficult to be prevented, especially on 10-class datasets. Table XV also shows that all 6 protections’ performances are degraded from VHNN to VSNN, and they all fail to thwart MC on CIFAR10 in VSNN, suggesting that FL practitioners should avoid using VSNN in production.

8.5.3 Evaluating Protections against Model Inversion

Model inversion (MI) attack has been studied in [14] and  [17]. The former focuses on VSNN and it does not investigate any protection mechanism, while the latter applies MI attack to VHNN without top model. We investigate the MI in both VSNN and VHNN, and conduct evaluations using FMINST image dataset. We use SSIM and Acc to measure the privacy leakage ϵpsubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝\epsilon_{p} and utility loss ϵusubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑢\epsilon_{u}, respectively.

We first apply MixUp and PRECODE to defend against MI assuming the adversary party A knows the model structure of party B, the data owner. Table XVI reports the results. With more samples used to generate a new sample through MixUp, the privacy leakage ϵpsubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝\epsilon_{p} decreases, and the utility loss ϵusubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑢\epsilon_{u} increases. Party B can adjust the privacy-utility trade-off by controlling the number of mix-upped samples according to their privacy budget. PRECODE reduces ϵpsubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝\epsilon_{p} to 0.02 in both VSNN and VHNN, with ϵusubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑢\epsilon_{u} of 0.07 in VHNN and ϵusubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑢\epsilon_{u} of 0.68 in VSNN, respectively, demonstrating the effectiveness of PRECODE in thwarting MI on image data.

In production VNN that involves complicated neural network structures [25], it is challenging for the adversary to obtain the model structure of the data owners. We investigate this scenario where the adversary trains the shadow model with a different model structure from that of the data owner to mount an MI attack. Table XVII reports that, in both VHNN and VSNN, the privacy leakage ϵpsubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝\epsilon_{p} drops noticeably when the adversary adopts different convolution layers and dramatically when it uses fully-connected layers. This suggests that MI can be prevented if data owners do not reveal their model structures.

Takeaways for VNN:
(1) Generally, Marvell can thwart NS and DS attacks successfully, and it is robust to the choice of protection strength.

(2) The six protection mechanisms evaluated in VNN have difficulty thwarting the MC attack. It calls for more effective MC-targeted protection mechanisms.

(3) FL practitioners should avoid adopting VSNN in production because VSNN makes privacy protection harder.

(4) In production VNN, keeping the model structure confidential can prevent the MI attack.

9 Conclusions and Future Work

We propose an evaluation framework that formulates the privacy-utility evaluation problem. It guides us to comprehensively evaluate a range of protection mechanisms against most of the state-of-the-art privacy attacks for three widely deployed VFL algorithms. These evaluations may help FL practitioners select appropriate protection mechanisms given specific requirements. Our future works have two directions: (1) integrating the efficiency aspect into our evaluation framework for supporting more comprehensive evaluations on VFL; (2) applying our evaluation framework to evaluate widely-adopted protection mechanisms in HFL.

Appendix B Datasets

In this section, we describe each dataset in detail.

Default Credit (Credit for short) consists of 23 features including user demographics, history of payments, and bill statements, etc., with users’ default payment as the label. The ratio of positive to negative samples is 1 : 4. We assign the first 13 samples to party B and the rest 10 features and label column to party A to simulate 2-party VFL setting. This dataset is used for VLR.

Vehicle111https://www.csie.ntu.edu.tw/~cjlin/libsvmtools/datasets/multiclass.html is for classifying the types of moving vehicles in a distributed sensor network. There are 3 types of vehicles. We choose samples of the first two types to form a binary classification dataset. Each sample has 50 acoustic features and 50 seismic features. To simulate the 2-party VFL setting, party A holds acoustic features and labels, while party B holds seismic features. The ratio of positive to negative samples is approximately 1 : 1. Each party has 40000 training samples, 5000 validation samples, and 5000 testing samples. This dataset is used for VLR.

NUSWIDE contains 634-dimensional low-level image features extracted from Flickr and 1000-dimensional corresponding text features. To simulate the 2-party VFL setting, party A holds image features and labels, while party B holds the text features. There are 81 ground truth labels. We build the dataset for our desired setting by selecting a subset of these labeled samples. Specifically, NUWSIDE10 is for the 10-class classification task. NUWSIDE2-imb is for the imbalanced binary classification task, in which the ratio of positive to negative samples is 1:9:191:9. NUWSIDE2-bal is for the balanced binary classification task, in which the ratio of positive to negative samples is 1:2:121:2. All the three datasets are used for VNN.

Criteo is for predicting click-through rate. It contains 26 categorical features and 13 continuous features. We transform categorical features into embeddings with fixed dimensions before feeding them the model. To simulate the 2-party VFL setting, we equally divide both kinds of features into two parts, so that each party has a mixture of categorical and continuous features. Party A owns the labels. The ratio of positive samples to negative samples is 1:16:1161:16. To reduce the computational complexity, we randomly select 100000 samples as the training set and 20000 samples as the test set.

BHI (Breast Histopathology Images) is used for binary classification task. It contains 277,524 slide mount images of breast cancer specimens from several patients. A positive label indicates Invasive Ductal Carcinoma (IDC) positve, which is a subtype of breast cancers. To simulate the 2-party VFL setting, we choose two images of a patient that have the same label to form a VFL sample, and each party is assigned one image. Party A owns the labels. The ratio between positive and negative samples is around 1:2.5:12.51:2.5. We randomly select data of 80%percent8080\% patients as training set and the rest as test set.

CIFAR10 contains images with shape 32×32×33232332\times 32\times 3. To simulate the 2-party VFL setting, each image is cut horizontally in the middle into two halves and each participating party holds one half of the image.

Fashion-MNIST contains images with shape 28×28×12828128\times 28\times 1. To simulate the 2-party VFL setting, each image is cut horizontally in the middle into two halves and each participating party holds one half of the image. This dataset is used for model inversion attack.

Appendix C Evaluations on Protection Mechanisms against MC Attack in VNN

Figure 11 shows the experimental results of the chosen protection mechanisms against MC attack in VHNN and VSNN, respectively. Specifically, each subfigure depicts the privacy leakage (y𝑦y axis) trend for every protection strength of a target protection mechanism with the increasing auxiliary sample size (x𝑥x axis). The legend presents protection strength values and their corresponding utility loss.

Figures 11 illustrates that the adversary generally obtains more knowledge payoff on the labels when it uses smaller amount of auxiliary samples (80 for CIFAR10 or 40 for the other datasets). The intuition behind this phenomenon is that the increment of the attacker’s prior knowledge on labels becomes larger than that of the attacker’s posterior knowledge on labels, as the number of auxiliary samples increases.
